    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-08-01T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-08-01T08:00:00-05:00" n="416"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d416">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 659.119/410</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Denmark</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_GSU1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grant-Smith</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Copenhagen</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-08-01T14:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 1, 1918, 2 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received August 2, 2.16 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2571. My 2564, July 30, 8 p.m.<note n="1" xml:id="d416fn1">Not printed.</note> [I
                    understand] that as a result of a conference yesterday attended by the Prime
                    Minister, the Minister of Foreign Affairs, representatives of the associations
                    and of agriculture, and Mr. <persName>H. N. Andersen</persName> for shipping,
                    telegraphic instructions were sent last night to the Danish delegates now at
                    Washington to offer further concessions as to tonnage and the reduction of
                    exporting to Germany. Mr. <persName>Andersen</persName> read me the telegram
                    which confers broader powers on the delegates, authorizes reopening the
                    negotiations on these lines, and urges them to establish mutual confidence. The
                    desire to reach a speedy agreement appears so keen that it seems probable the
                    proposals might be entirely recast to suit the Allied interest. Copy to
                    London.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_GSU1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Grant-Smith</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
